  2018,"04",/general-conference/2018/04/the-prophet-of-god,Elder Neil L. Andersen,57,"President Dallin H. Oaks once said:"
  2018,"04",/general-conference/2018/04/the-prophet-of-god,Elder Neil L. Andersen,58,"“In a 1988 interview … I explained my attitude toward attempts to supply mortal reasons for divine revelation:"
  2018,"04",/general-conference/2018/04/the-prophet-of-god,Elder Neil L. Andersen,59,"“‘If you read the scriptures with this question in mind, “Why did the Lord command this or why did he command that,” you find that in less than one in a hundred commands was any reason given. It’s not the pattern of the Lord to give reasons. We [mortals] can put reasons to revelation. We can put reasons to commandments. When we do, we’re on our own. Some people put reasons to the [revelation] … , and they turned out to be spectacularly wrong. There is a lesson in that. … I decided a long time ago that I had faith in the command and I had no faith in the reasons that had been suggested for it.’ …"
  2018,"04",/general-conference/2018/04/the-prophet-of-god,Elder Neil L. Andersen,60,"“‘… The whole set of reasons seemed to me to be unnecessary risk taking. … Let’s don’t make the mistake that’s been made in the past, … trying to put reasons to revelation. The reasons turn out to be man-made to a great extent. The revelations are what we sustain as the will of the Lord and that’s where safety lies’” (Life’s Lessons Learned[2011], 68–69)."
  2018,"04",/general-conference/2018/04/the-prophet-of-god,Elder Neil L. Andersen,61,"Exodus 20:14."
  2018,"04",/general-conference/2018/04/the-prophet-of-god,Elder Neil L. Andersen,62,"Mosiah 15:7."
  2018,"04",/general-conference/2018/04/the-prophet-of-god,Elder Neil L. Andersen,63,"Russell M. Nelson, in Lane Johnson, “Russell M. Nelson: A Study in Obedience,”Ensign,Aug. 1982, 24;Tambuli,Jan. 1983, 26."
  2018,"04",/general-conference/2018/04/the-prophet-of-god,Elder Neil L. Andersen,64,"President Henry B. Eyring said: “Another fallacy is to believe that the choice to accept or not accept the counsel of prophets is no more than deciding whether to accept good advice and gain its benefits or to stay where we are. But the choice not to take prophetic counsel changes the very ground upon which we stand. It becomes more dangerous. The failure to take prophetic counsel lessens our power to take inspired counsel in the future. The best time to have decided to help Noah build the ark was the first time he asked. Each time he asked after that, each failure to respond would have lessened sensitivity to the Spirit. And so each time his request would have seemed more foolish, until the rain came. And then it was too late” (“Finding Safety in Counsel,”Ensign,May 1997, 25)."
  2018,"04",/general-conference/2018/04/the-prophet-of-god,Elder Neil L. Andersen,65,"3 Nephi 20:24."
  2018,"04",/general-conference/2018/04/the-prophet-of-god,Elder Neil L. Andersen,66,"Matthew 16:16; see alsoJohn 6:69."
